### Definition and Terminology

**Definition 1.2.1** (Imaginary Unit):

The imaginary unit, i, is a number such that \(\,\mathrm{i}^{2}=-1\,\). Hence, \(\,\mathrm{i}=\sqrt{-1}\,\).

Thus, the square root of any negative real number can then be written in the form of \(a\mathrm{i}\), where \(a\) is a positive real number.

For example, \(\sqrt{-3}=\sqrt{(3)(-1)}=\sqrt{3}\sqrt{-1}=\left(\sqrt{3}\right)\mathrm{i}\,\).

**Definition 1.2.2** (Complex Number in Cartesian form):

A complex number, \(\,z\in\mathbb{C}\,\), is a number of the form \(\,x+\mathrm{i}y\,\), where \(\,x,\,y\in\mathbb{R}\,\).

The symbol \(\,\mathbb{C}\,\) is used to denote the set of complex numbers.

_Hierarchy of the number system:_

\[\begin{array}{ll}\text{Complex Numbers, }\mathbb{C}\\ &\text{Real Numbers, }\mathbb{R}\quad\text{Purely Imaginary Numbers}\\ &\text{Rational Numbers, }\mathbb{Q}\quad\text{Irrational Numbers}\\ &\text{Integers, }\mathbb{Z}\quad\text{Fractions}\\ &\text{I}\end{array}\]

Negative Integers \(\,\mathbb{Z}\quad\text{Zero}\quad\text{Positive Integers}\)

**Definition 1.2.3** (Real and Imaginary Parts of a Complex Number):

If \(z=x+\mathrm{i}y\), \(x\), \(y\in\mathbb{R}\), then

\(x\) is the **real** part of \(z\) and is denoted by \(\mathrm{Re}\left(z\right)\). (i.e. \(\mathrm{Re}\left(z\right)=x\))

\(y\) is the **imaginary** part of \(z\) is denoted by \(\mathrm{Im}\left(z\right)\). (i.e. \(\mathrm{Im}\left(z\right)=y\))

**Note:**

1. If \(x=0\), then \(z=\mathrm{i}y\) is a **purely imaginary** number.
2. If \(y=0\), then \(z=x\) is a **real** number.
3. \(\mathrm{Im}\left(z\right)=y\) is a real number. \(\mathrm{Im}\left(z\right)\) is **NOT** iy.

**Definition 1.2.4** (Equality of Complex Numbers):

Two complex numbers are **equal** if and only if their real and imaginary parts are equal.

That is, given that \(z_{1}=x_{1}+\mathrm{i}y_{1}\) and \(z_{2}=x_{2}+\mathrm{i}y_{2}\) where \(x_{1},x_{2},y_{1},y_{2}\in\mathbb{R}\), then

\(z_{1}=z_{2}\)\(\Leftrightarrow\)\(x_{1}=x_{2}\)and \(y_{1}=y_{2}\).

**Note:**

1. \(z=0\)\(\Leftrightarrow\)\(x=0\) and \(y=0\)
2. Inequalities do not apply to complex numbers that are not real numbers. For example, we cannot say \(2+\mathrm{i}\) is larger or smaller than \(2-\mathrm{i}\).

