### Modulus and Argument of a Complex Number

\(\underline{\text{Im}}\)

Without loss of generality, \(P\) represents the complex number \(z=x+\mathrm{i}\mathrm{y}\), where \(x,y\in\mathbb{R}^{+}\). We have:

**Definition 5.2.1** (Modulus):

The **modulus** of a complex number \(z=x+\mathrm{i}\mathrm{y}\) is defined as \(\sqrt{x^{2}+y^{2}}\), and is denoted by \(\left|z\right|\).

Geometrically, it is the _distance_ between the origin and the point \(P\), i.e., the magnitude of \(\overline{OP}\).

**Note:**

1. \(|z|\) is always a non-negative real number, e.g., \(\left|-3+4\mathrm{i}\right|=\sqrt{\left(-3\right)^{2}+4^{2}}=5\).
2. From vector subtraction (diagram from parallelogram law of vector subtraction), we see that \(\left|z_{2}-z_{1}\right|=\left|\overline{P_{1}P_{2}}\right|\) is the distance between \(P_{1}\) and \(P_{2}\).

**Definition 5.2.2 (Argument)**

The **argument** of \(z\) is defined as \(\theta\), the angle between \(OP\) and the positive real axis, and is denoted by \(\arg(z)\).

**Note:**

1. \(\theta\) is positive when measured anti-clockwise from the positive real axis and is negative when measured clockwise from the positive real axis.
2. It is important that you first check the quadrant in which \(z\) lies before computing its argument.

